In C, you can cast a `double` to an `int` using the following syntax:

```c 
int myInt = (int) myDouble;
```

This will truncate the decimal part of the `double` and assign the remaining integer value to the `int`.

For example:

```c 
double myDouble = 10.9;
int myInt = (int) myDouble; // myInt becomes 10, losing the.9 part.

Please note that this is a truncation, not a rounding.

```
